The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Nation at a Glance

 Rice raids on food officials

 new delhi (PTI): The CBI on Monday conducted searches at 11 places across four states against some officials of the Food Corporation of India (FCI) for allegedly purchasing sub-standard rice and causing a loss of Rs 320 crore to the exchequer.

 The searches ? at eight places in Punjab and one each in Bihar, Uttar Pradesh and Andhra Pradesh ? were carried out after the CBI registered three cases against more than 50 FCI officials, including senior regional manager K. Shiva Prasad, an IAS officer.

 The cases were registered under various sections of the Indian Penal Code and the Prevention of Corruption Act.

 The CBI had carried out surprise checks at FCI godowns in September and October last year during which 451 samples were collected from 12 locations in Punjab and were sent to the Central Grain Analysis Laboratory.

 Suitcase scare at airport

 chennai (PTI): An unclaimed suitcase and a middle-aged man running pell-mell towards the runway caused a flutter at Chennai airport on Monday.

 The trolley-suitcase was noticed in the security hold area by an official at the Kamaraj domestic terminal. The Bureau of Civil Aviation Security was informed and the suitcase was removed to a safer place, airport sources said.

 Meanwhile, a man, aged about 50 years, scaled a gate and was seen running towards the runway. An official overpowered him after a chase and handed him over to police.

 Soldiers shot

 srinagar (PTI): Two army soldiers were shot dead by their colleague on Sunday in Jammu and Kashmirs Pulwama district, official sources said.

 Lance Naik Abdesh Kumar of 55 Rashtriya Rifles killed sepoys Gurmail Singh and Kukander Singh inside their camp after a heated argument.

 Highway shelter

 jammu (PTI): The Jammu and Kashmir disaster management authority will set up seven shelters for commuters stranded on the Jammu-Srinagar highway due to snowfall and landslides. The sheds will provide bedding and food.

 Kargil probe

 New Delhi (PTI): The Supreme Court has granted four weeks to the Centre to spell out the status of the probe into 25 defence deals relating to the Kargil conflict. The deals include the casket-purchase scam which allegedly caused a loss of Rs 2,000 crore to the exchequer.Meeruts Noor Jahan gave birth to a baby boy on Saturday in a dispensary during the Haj in Saudi Arabia. Another Indian Haj pilgrim, Bano, had delivered a baby on December 28.




